column10:
Research Information and Participant Consent  

   

 

Welcome
to the study. Thanks for taking the time to complete this survey!   



Your participation: Your
participation involves completing some personality questionnaires and answering
some questions about current events. The entire study will take less than 20
minutes to complete.    



The plan for this study has been reviewed
by a Research Ethics Board at the University of Alberta (Pro00100206). If you have questions
about your rights or how research should be conducted, you can call (780)
492-2615.  This office is independent of the researchers. 
 

Purpose: You are invited to participate in a study conducted by
researchers from the Department of Psychology at the University of Alberta that
examines personality and perceptions of current events.  

 

Your participation: Your
participation involves completing some personality questionnaires and answering
some questions about current events. The entire study will take less than 20 minutes
to complete. You will be compensated by Lucid for your time.      


 

Your rights: Your decision to participate in this study is entirely voluntary and
you may decide at any time to withdraw from the study. It is your right to
terminate participation at any time you wish. You may also decline to answer any
of the individual questions. Any responses made by individual participants on
the questionnaires will remain confidential. Questionnaires will be identified
only by a researcher-assigned code number. Only researchers associated with the
project will have access to the questionnaires. The results of this study may
be presented at scholarly conferences, published in professional journals, or
presented in class lectures. Only grouped (aggregate) data will be presented.
The data will be securely stored on a flash drive in a locked drawer in the
researcher’s laboratory for at least five years. Hard copies of the data will
be destroyed after the five-year time period has elapsed and the data will be
shredded. You may not withdraw your data after the study has been completed as,
Lucid ID information will be removed and we will have no way to identify your
response. You will however be given an opportunity to withdraw your data at the
end of the study without penalty.     


 

Benefits and risks: There are no direct benefits to the participants for this study,
however, this research can potentially contribute to the advancement of our
understanding of psychological processes. There are no foreseeable
psychological or social risks associated with participation in this study.
Should you experience any distress, you will always have the option to leave
the study or to not answer any questions you are not comfortable with.
Moreover, if any risks should arise, the researcher will inform the participants
immediately.       

 

Contact information: If you have any questions or comments about this study, please
contact the principal investigator, Dr. Kyle Nash (knash@ualberta.ca).

Read carefully 

 
Please imagine that you were provided with the total amount of $200.



It would be entirely up to you how much money you would keep for yourself, and how much you would give to charity organizations who are working full-time to protect people from the Coronavirus (COVID-19).

 

Your identity would remain 100% anonymous, regardless of your choice.

No one else would know how much you decided to keep and how much you decided to give.

 
If this was a real choice:

 
How much (0-100%) would you give to charity?

 

Please indicate below how much you would keep to yourself, how much you would give to a national charity in Aotearoa New Zealand, providing medical support to people in your own country, and how much you would give to an international charity, providing medical support to people in need all over the world. - What would you KEEP to yourself

column96:
Please think of this ladder as representing where people stand in Aotearoa New Zealand. 

 

At the top of this ladder are the people who are the best off – those who have the most money, the most education and the most respected jobs. At the bottom are the people who are the worst off – who have the least money, least education, and the least respected jobs or no jobs. The higher up you are on this ladder, the closer you are to the people at the very top, the lower you are, the closer you are to the people at the very bottom.

 



 

Where would you place yourself on this ladder to represent where you think you stand at this time in your life, compared to other people in Aotearoa New Zealand?

column118:
Thank you for participating in this study.

 

Today’s study is a large international collaboration designed to better understand the psychological outcomes of the COVID-19 pandemic. These data will be used by researchers to examine a variety of important questions about psychological reaction to the ongoing pandemic. By completing this survey, you have directly contributed to a better understanding of the psychological outcomes of these unique times.

 

Thank you for your participation.

 

If you have any questions or concerns, feel free to contact:

Dr Andrew Vonasch

School of Psychology, Speech and Hearing

University of Canterbury

andrew.vonasch@canterbury.ac.nz





Information for counseling services are listed below:

Lifeline: Call 0800 543 354

Need to talk?: Call or text 1737
